A strong storm arrives today with snow beginning early afternoon in the Cascades before spreading east into the late afternoon and evening. ...WINTER STORM WARNING IN EFFECT FROM 4 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO NOON PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 4 to 6 inches in the valleys and 6 to 12 inches in the mountains. * WHERE...Colville, Northport, Deer Park, Chewelah, Newport, Kettle Falls, Springdale-Hunters Road, Orin-Rice Road, Flowery Trail Road, Republic, Inchelium, Wauconda, Chesaw Road, Highway 20 Wauconda Summit, Boulder Creek Road, and Sherman Pass. * WHEN...From 4 PM this afternoon to noon PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Patchy blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
regions: ['Lower Columbia and I - 5 Corridor in Cowlitz County']
description: ...MORE SNOW EXPECTED IN THE OREGON COASTAL RANGES AND THE WASHINGTON AND OREGON CASCADES WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY... .A strong area of low pressure off the Pacific Northwest coast will spread moisture inland today. Relatively low snow levels are expected to result in moderate snow accumulations affecting much of Southwest Washington, the Columbia River Gorge, and the hills above 1000 to 1500 feet around Northwest Oregon midday today through early Thursday. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 10 AM THIS MORNING TO 4 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations ranging from a dusting to 1 inch for the valleys, and 1 to 3 inches for the hills. * WHERE...In Washington, I-5 Corridor in Cowlitz County. In Oregon, Lower Columbia. * WHEN...From 10 AM this morning to 4 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. * ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snow level will rise to around 1000 feet later this afternoon, remaining near 1000 feet tonight.

title: High Wind Warning
description: ...HIGH WIND WARNING IN EFFECT FROM 1 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 10 PM PST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Southeast winds 35 to 45 mph with gusts of 55 to 60 mph expected. * WHERE...North Coast and Central Coast. * WHEN...From 1 PM this afternoon to 10 PM PST this evening. * IMPACTS...Damaging winds will blow down trees and power lines. Power outages are expected. Travel will be difficult, especially for high profile vehicles.

Relatively low snow levels are expected to result in moderate snow accumulations affecting much of Southwest Washington, the Columbia River Gorge, and the hills above 1000 to 1500 feet around Northwest Oregon midday today through early Thursday. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 10 AM THIS MORNING TO 4 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 3 to 6 inches. Winds gusting as high as 40 mph. * WHERE...South Washington Cascade Foothills. * WHEN...From 10 AM this morning to 4 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. * ADDITIONAL DETAILS...A few pockets of freezing rain are possible in the valleys tonight.

title: High Wind Warning
description: ...HIGH WIND WARNING IN EFFECT FROM 1 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 10 PM PST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Southeast winds 30 to 40 mph with gusts up to 55 mph expected. * WHERE...Admiralty Inlet Area. * WHEN...From 1 PM this afternoon to 10 PM PST this evening. * IMPACTS...Damaging winds will blow down trees and power lines. Widespread power outages are expected. Travel will be difficult, especially for high profile vehicles.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...ANOTHER WINTER STORM TO BRING HEAVY SNOW TO THE NORTHERN VALLEYS AND MOUNTAINS LATE TODAY INTO THURSDAY MORNING... .Cold wind chills as low as 15 degrees below zero will continue down the Okanogan Valley this morning. A strong storm arrives today with snow beginning early afternoon in the Cascades before spreading east into the late afternoon and evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 10 AM THIS MORNING TO 10 PM PST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 2 to 4 inches. * WHERE...Wenatchee, Chelan, Entiat, Cashmere, Number 1 Canyon, Number 2 Canyon, Pangborn Airport, Waterville, Mansfield, and Badger Mountain Road. * WHEN...From 10 AM this morning to 10 PM PST this evening. * IMPACTS...Travel could be difficult. The hazardous conditions could impact the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...ANOTHER WINTER STORM TO BRING HEAVY SNOW TO THE NORTHERN VALLEYS AND MOUNTAINS LATE TODAY INTO THURSDAY MORNING... .Cold wind chills as low as 15 degrees below zero will continue down the Okanogan Valley this morning. A strong storm arrives today with snow beginning early afternoon in the Cascades before spreading east into the late afternoon and evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 AM PST THURSDAY... ...WINTER STORM WATCH IS CANCELLED... * WHAT...Snow. Snow accumulations of 5 to 9 inches with local amounts to 12 inches in the higher elevations. * WHERE...Leavenworth, Mazama, Twisp, Winthrop, Stehekin, Conconully, Blewett Pass, Loup Loup Pass, Plain, and Holden Village. * WHEN...Until 6 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult around the region, particularly on the Highway 2 approach to Stevens Pass and across Loup Loup and Blewett passes.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...A brief break in snow this morning before next round arrives this afternoon. Additional snow accumulations of 2 to 16 inches, heaviest above 1000 feet this afternoon into Thursday. Winds gusting as high as 45 mph. * WHERE...Cascade mountains and valleys of Whatcom and Skagit Counties, including Maple Falls, the Mount Baker Ski Area, Newhalem, Lyman, and Concrete. * WHEN...Until 6 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...MORE SNOW EXPECTED IN THE OREGON COASTAL RANGES AND THE WASHINGTON AND OREGON CASCADES WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY... .A strong area of low pressure off the Pacific Northwest coast will spread moisture inland today. Relatively low snow levels are expected to result in moderate snow accumulations affecting much of Southwest Washington, the Columbia River Gorge, and the hills above 1000 to 1500 feet around Northwest Oregon midday today through early Thursday. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 10 AM THIS MORNING TO 4 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations ranging from 1 inch or less in the lowlands, with 1 to 4 inches expected in the hills. Heaviest accumulations will occur in the hills above 800 feet. The hazardous conditions could impact the evening commute. Spotty light freezing rain is possible tonight.

A strong storm arrives today with snow beginning early afternoon in the Cascades before spreading east into the late afternoon and evening. ...WIND CHILL ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 10 AM PST THIS MORNING... ...WINTER STORM WARNING IN EFFECT FROM 1 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 10 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...For the Winter Storm Warning, heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 4 to 6 inches. For the Wind Chill Advisory, very cold wind chills. Wind chills as low as 20 below zero. * WHERE...Omak, Okanogan, Brewster, Bridgeport, Oroville, Nespelem, and Disautel Pass. * WHEN...For the Winter Storm Warning, from 1 PM this afternoon to 10 AM PST Thursday. For the Wind Chill Advisory, until 10 AM PST this morning. * IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. The hazardous conditions could impact the evening commute. The cold wind chills could cause frostbite on exposed skin in as little as 30 minutes.

title: Wind Advisory
description: ...WIND ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 4 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 1 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Southeast winds 25 to 35 mph with gusts up to 45 mph expected. * WHERE...Everett and Vicinity. * WHEN...From 4 PM this afternoon to 1 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Gusty winds could blow around unsecured objects. Tree limbs could be blown down and a few power outages may result.

title: Winter Storm Warning
description: ...ANOTHER WINTER STORM TO BRING HEAVY SNOW TO THE NORTHERN VALLEYS AND MOUNTAINS LATE TODAY INTO THURSDAY MORNING... .Cold wind chills as low as 15 degrees below zero will continue down the Okanogan Valley this morning. A strong storm arrives today with snow beginning early afternoon in the Cascades before spreading east into the late afternoon and evening. ...WINTER STORM WARNING IN EFFECT FROM 4 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO NOON PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 4 to 6 inches in the valleys and 6 to 12 inches in the mountains. * WHERE...Colville, Northport, Deer Park, Chewelah, Newport, Kettle Falls, Springdale-Hunters Road, Orin-Rice Road, Flowery Trail Road, Republic, Inchelium, Wauconda, Chesaw Road, Highway 20 Wauconda Summit, Boulder Creek Road, and Sherman Pass. * WHEN...From 4 PM this afternoon to noon PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Patchy blowing snow could significantly reduce visibility. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning or evening commute.

title: High Wind Warning
description: ...HIGH WIND WARNING IN EFFECT FROM 1 PM THIS AFTERNOON TO 10 PM PST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...East to southeast winds 30 to 40 mph with gusts of 55 to 60 mph expected. * WHERE...East Puget Sound Lowlands. * WHEN...From 1 PM this afternoon to 10 PM PST this evening. * IMPACTS...Damaging winds combined with the heavy wet snow will blow down trees and power lines. Power outages are likely. Travel will be difficult, especially for high profile vehicles.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...A brief break in snow this morning before next round arrives this afternoon. Additional snow accumulations of 2 to 16 inches, heaviest above 1000 feet this afternoon into Thursday. Winds gusting as high as 45 mph. * WHERE...Cascade mountains and valleys of Whatcom and Skagit Counties, including Maple Falls, the Mount Baker Ski Area, Newhalem, Lyman, and Concrete. * WHEN...Until 6 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.

A strong storm arrives today with snow beginning early afternoon in the Cascades before spreading east into the late afternoon and evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 AM PST THURSDAY... ...WINTER STORM WATCH IS CANCELLED... * WHAT...Snow. Snow accumulations of 5 to 9 inches with local amounts to 12 inches in the higher elevations. * WHERE...Leavenworth, Mazama, Twisp, Winthrop, Stehekin, Conconully, Blewett Pass, Loup Loup Pass, Plain, and Holden Village. * WHEN...Until 6 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult around the region, particularly on the Highway 2 approach to Stevens Pass and across Loup Loup and Blewett passes.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...MORE SNOW EXPECTED IN THE OREGON COASTAL RANGES AND THE WASHINGTON AND OREGON CASCADES WEDNESDAY INTO THURSDAY... .A strong area of low pressure off the Pacific Northwest coast will spread moisture inland today. Relatively low snow levels are expected to result in moderate snow accumulations affecting much of Southwest Washington, the Columbia River Gorge, and the hills above 1000 to 1500 feet around Northwest Oregon midday today through early Thursday. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 10 AM THIS MORNING TO 4 AM PST THURSDAY... * WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations ranging from 1 inch or less in the lowlands, with 1 to 4 inches expected in the hills. Heaviest accumulations will occur in the hills above 800 feet. Winds gusting to 45 mph near the Gorge. * WHERE...Greater Vancouver Area, mainly above 500 feet. * WHEN...From 10 AM this morning to 4 AM PST Thursday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the evening commute. Spotty light freezing rain is possible tonight.

description: ...WINTER STORM WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 4 PM PST THIS AFTERNOON... * WHAT...Heavy snow has ended this morning. Next round arrives late this morning into the afternoon hours. Additional snow accumulations of 1 to 5 inches are expected with locally higher amounts possible. * WHERE...Eastern Strait of Juan de Fuca lowlands, including Port Angeles, Sequim, and Blyn, Western Strait of Juan de Fuca lowlands, including Sekiu, Clallam Bay, and Joyce and North coast, including Neah Bay, Forks, and Queets. * WHEN...Until 4 PM PST this afternoon. * IMPACTS...Travel, including the morning commute, could be very difficult given heavy snow that fell overnight.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...WINTRY MIX EXPECTED THIS MORNING... .The wintry mix of light freezing rain and snow will be pushing into south central Wisconsin through 8 am. A light accumulation of glaze less than one tenth inch and snowfall less than one inch is expected. The wintry mix will likely cause slippery spots on untreated roads and walks. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A mix of freezing drizzle and light snow. Ice accumulations of a light glaze and snow accumulations of less than a half inch. * WHERE...Portions of south central Wisconsin. * WHEN...From 6 AM to noon CST Wednesday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Special Weather Statement
regions: ['Brown', 'Calumet', 'Door', 'Florence', 'Forest', 'Kewaunee', 'Langlade', 'Lincoln', 'Manitowoc', 'Marathon', 'Menominee', 'Northern Marinette County', 'Northern Oconto County', 'Oneida', 'Outagamie', 'Portage', 'Shawano', 'Southern Marinette County', 'Southern Oconto County', 'Vilas', 'Waupaca', 'Waushara', 'Winnebago', 'Wood']
description: ...SNOW EXPECTED TO RESULT IN SLIPPERY TRAVEL CONDITIONS TODAY INTO TONIGHT... Snow will develop across the area during the mid-day hours, then diminish by early evening. The snow in central and east-central Wisconsin could transition to freezing drizzle as it tapers off late today and this evening. An inch or two of snow accumulation is expected across most of the area, with 2 to 3 inches possible in far north-central Wisconsin. The snow is likely to result in slippery travel conditions. Although the morning commute will not be affected, the afternoon commute is likely to be slowed by the snow. Be sure to allow for some extra travel time once the snow begins Much colder air will surge into the area overnight as the weather system producing the snow shifts off to the east. By daybreak Thursday, temperatures will drop to around zero across central and north-central Wisconsin, and into the teens along the Lakeshore. This will drive wind chill indices into the 10 below to 20 below zero range across most of the area, and to 5 below to 10 below along the Lakeshore. Wind chills such as this indicate exposed skin can suffer frostbite in as little as 30 minutes. Be sure to dress accordingly before heading out on Thursday morning. The gusty winds ushering the colder air into the area could also produce some drifting snow tonight, mainly in rural areas. Of greater significance is the potential for the rapid arrival of the colder air to cause any lingering water on the roads to re- freeze into glare ice and produce very slippery conditions. Be prepared for the possibility of icy spots on roads and sidewalks tomorrow morning.

An inch or two of snow accumulation is expected across most of the area, with 2 to 3 inches possible in far north-central Wisconsin. The snow is likely to result in slippery travel conditions. Although the morning commute will not be affected, the afternoon commute is likely to be slowed by the snow. Be sure to allow for some extra travel time once the snow begins Much colder air will surge into the area overnight as the weather system producing the snow shifts off to the east. By daybreak Thursday, temperatures will drop to around zero across central and north-central Wisconsin, and into the teens along the Lakeshore. This will drive wind chill indices into the 10 below to 20 below zero range across most of the area, and to 5 below to 10 below along the Lakeshore. Wind chills such as this indicate exposed skin can suffer frostbite in as little as 30 minutes. Be sure to dress accordingly before heading out on Thursday morning. The gusty winds ushering the colder air into the area could also produce some drifting snow tonight, mainly in rural areas. Of greater significance is the potential for the rapid arrival of the colder air to cause any lingering water on the roads to re- freeze into glare ice and produce very slippery conditions. Be prepared for the possibility of icy spots on roads and sidewalks tomorrow morning.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...WINTRY MIX EXPECTED THIS MORNING... .The wintry mix of light freezing rain and snow will be pushing into south central Wisconsin through 8 am. A light accumulation of glaze less than one tenth inch and snowfall less than one inch is expected. The wintry mix will likely cause slippery spots on untreated roads and walks. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A mix of freezing drizzle and light snow. Ice accumulations of a light glaze and snow accumulations of less than a half inch. * WHERE...Portions of south central Wisconsin. * WHEN...From 6 AM to noon CST Wednesday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

A light accumulation of glaze less than one tenth inch and snowfall less than one inch is expected. The wintry mix will likely cause slippery spots on untreated roads and walks. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A mix of freezing drizzle and light snow. Ice accumulations of a light glaze and snow accumulations of less than a half inch. * WHERE...Portions of south central Wisconsin. * WHEN...From 6 AM to noon CST Wednesday. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Special Weather Statement
regions: ['Brown', 'Calumet', 'Door', 'Florence', 'Forest', 'Kewaunee', 'Langlade', 'Lincoln', 'Manitowoc', 'Marathon', 'Menominee', 'Northern Marinette County', 'Northern Oconto County', 'Oneida', 'Outagamie', 'Portage', 'Shawano', 'Southern Marinette County', 'Southern Oconto County', 'Vilas', 'Waupaca', 'Waushara', 'Winnebago', 'Wood']
description: ...SNOW EXPECTED TO RESULT IN SLIPPERY TRAVEL CONDITIONS TODAY INTO TONIGHT... Snow will develop across the area during the mid-day hours, then diminish by early evening. The snow in central and east-central Wisconsin could transition to freezing drizzle as it tapers off late today and this evening. An inch or two of snow accumulation is expected across most of the area, with 2 to 3 inches possible in far north-central Wisconsin. The snow is likely to result in slippery travel conditions. Although the morning commute will not be affected, the afternoon commute is likely to be slowed by the snow. Be sure to allow for some extra travel time once the snow begins Much colder air will surge into the area overnight as the weather system producing the snow shifts off to the east. By daybreak Thursday, temperatures will drop to around zero across central and north-central Wisconsin, and into the teens along the Lakeshore. This will drive wind chill indices into the 10 below to 20 below zero range across most of the area, and to 5 below to 10 below along the Lakeshore. Wind chills such as this indicate exposed skin can suffer frostbite in as little as 30 minutes. Be sure to dress accordingly before heading out on Thursday morning. The gusty winds ushering the colder air into the area could also produce some drifting snow tonight, mainly in rural areas. Of greater significance is the potential for the rapid arrival of the colder air to cause any lingering water on the roads to re- freeze into glare ice and produce very slippery conditions. Be prepared for the possibility of icy spots on roads and sidewalks tomorrow morning.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory

regions: ['Brown', 'Calumet', 'Door', 'Florence', 'Forest', 'Kewaunee', 'Langlade', 'Lincoln', 'Manitowoc', 'Marathon', 'Menominee', 'Northern Marinette County', 'Northern Oconto County', 'Oneida', 'Outagamie', 'Portage', 'Shawano', 'Southern Marinette County', 'Southern Oconto County', 'Vilas', 'Waupaca', 'Waushara', 'Winnebago', 'Wood']
description: ...SNOW EXPECTED TO RESULT IN SLIPPERY TRAVEL CONDITIONS TODAY INTO TONIGHT... Snow will develop across the area during the mid-day hours, then diminish by early evening. The snow in central and east-central Wisconsin could transition to freezing drizzle as it tapers off late today and this evening. An inch or two of snow accumulation is expected across most of the area, with 2 to 3 inches possible in far north-central Wisconsin. The snow is likely to result in slippery travel conditions. Although the morning commute will not be affected, the afternoon commute is likely to be slowed by the snow. Be sure to allow for some extra travel time once the snow begins Much colder air will surge into the area overnight as the weather system producing the snow shifts off to the east. By daybreak Thursday, temperatures will drop to around zero across central and north-central Wisconsin, and into the teens along the Lakeshore. This will drive wind chill indices into the 10 below to 20 below zero range across most of the area, and to 5 below to 10 below along the Lakeshore. Wind chills such as this indicate exposed skin can suffer frostbite in as little as 30 minutes. Be sure to dress accordingly before heading out on Thursday morning. The gusty winds ushering the colder air into the area could also produce some drifting snow tonight, mainly in rural areas. Of greater significance is the potential for the rapid arrival of the colder air to cause any lingering water on the roads to re- freeze into glare ice and produce very slippery conditions. Be prepared for the possibility of icy spots on roads and sidewalks tomorrow morning.

Although the morning commute will not be affected, the afternoon commute is likely to be slowed by the snow. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

title: Special Weather Statement
description: ...SNOW ACROSS UPPER MICHIGAN TODAY, BECOMING LAKE EFFECT TONIGHT... A band of snow will cross through Upper Michigan today bringing widespread snow from west to east through the afternoon. Snowfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches are expected across much of Upper Michigan, with locally up to 3 inches west and along the Wisconsin border through tonight. Behind this system, lake-effect snow will begin in the northwest wind snow belts with an additional 2 to 4 inches, locally up to 5 inches expected through tomorrow morning. Highest snowfall totals are expected along western Upper Michigan tonight. Looking ahead, a broad low pressure system will lift from the Central Plains through the Great Lakes region Friday night into Saturday. This low pressure system will bring widespread snow with moderate to possibly heavy snow. Stay tuned to changes in the forecast.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.

description: ...LIGHT SNOW TODAY... .Light snow is expected over the Northland today as a trough of low pressure moves eastward across the region. The greatest snow amounts will stretch from central Minnesota east into northwest Wisconsin. A swath of 1 to 3 inches of snow is forecast for the advisory area. Lake enhancement to the snow is expected along the South Shore of Lake Superior which will yield 3 to 5 inches for the northern tier of zones, with 1 to 3 inches for the southern tier. Snow will taper off from west to east during the afternoon and early evening. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM CST THIS EVENING... * WHAT...Snow with snow accumulations of 2 to 5 inches. * WHERE...Sawyer, Price, Iron, Burnett, Washburn, Douglas, Bayfield and Ashland Counties. This includes the Tribal Lands of the Red Cliff Band and the Bad River Reservation. * WHEN...Until 6 PM CST this evening. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions, including during the evening commute.

title: Winter Weather Advisory
description: ...Wintry Mix to Lead to Slick Roads This Morning... .A wintry mix of freezing drizzle and light snow will lead to slick roads along and south of Interstate 90 this morning, including during the morning commute. The freezing drizzle will continue to move into northeast Iowa and southwest Wisconsin through 8 AM and into the Interstate 90 corridor between 8 AM and 10 AM. Untreated roads and sidewalks, along with elevated surfaces such as bridges will be especially vulnerable to icing. Plan now for potential travel impacts, including slowdowns during the morning commute. ...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL NOON CST TODAY... * WHAT...A wintry mix of light snow and freezing drizzle. Total snow accumulations of half an inch or less and ice accumulations of a light glaze. * WHERE...In Iowa, Allamakee County. In Minnesota, Fillmore and Houston Counties. * WHEN...Through noon Today. * IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous conditions could impact the morning commute.
